  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has evolved significantly over the past century:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged as a concept in response to organized crime activities, particularly during Prohibition era in the United States\n- Initially focused on hiding proceeds from illegal activities like bootlegging and gambling\n\n2. Key Legislative Milestones:\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US): First major legal framework requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- 1986 Money Laundering Control Act (US): Criminalized money laundering as a distinct federal crime\n- 1989 Formation of Financial Action Task Force (FATF): Established international standards for combating money laundering\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention: Addressed drug trafficking proceeds\n- 2001 USA PATRIOT Act: Expanded anti-money laundering regulations post-9/11\n- Gradual global adoption of standardized reporting and compliance mechanisms\n\n4. Modern Approach:\n- Increasingly complex regulations\n- Focus on preventing terrorist financing\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Significant penalties for non-compliance\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving with technological advancements and emerging financial crime techniques.",
